Class PredicateList

java.lang.Object
  project3.three.Node
      project3.three.List
          project3.PredicateList
Direct Known Subclasses:
Query
public class PredicateList
extends List

A list of Predicates.

Syntax: PredicateList -→
Predicate ["," Predicate ]*

There are four properties that we need to define for a PredicateList:

  1. A PredicateList contains a list of Predicate. It is implemented as an ArrayList. We enforce the fact that it is a list of Predicate by only creating elements for the list using the createNode(Lex) method. The createNode(Lex) method below creates only Predicates. A Predicate is an instance of type Node so it can be added to an ArrayList.
  2. To determine whether to parse another Predicate and add it to the list we need to know whether lex.front() is in the first of Predicate. This is implemented by the method isInFirstOfListElement(Lex). The first of Predicate is {Identifier}. This is the default value and is defined in the List::isInFirstOfListElement(Lex). Thus, we do NOT override it here.
  3. A PredicateList is a list of one-or-more elements. This is the default value of a list and defined in List::getLengthConstraint(). We do NOT override it here.
  4. The elements of a PredicateList are separated by commas. This is defined in getSeparator() below. 
 Domain Definition
     predicateList       : Sequence<Predicate>
     variableInformation : VariableInformation 

 Instance Invariant:
     |predicateList| > 0 AND
     variableInformation ≠ null

createAllCombinations

protected boolean createAllCombinations(int i)
                                 throws ParserException
Recursively computes every combination of consants for the variables in the predicate list and checks to see if any combination makes all of the predicates in the predicate list true. A combination of constants that makes evey Predicate in the PredicateList true is called a solution.

Precondition: none
Postcondition: result = There exists a combination of constant substitutions, S, for the variables in variables[i..|variables-1], such that every predicate in the predicate list is true.

Parameters:
i - the ith variable for which we need to substitute constants from the domain.
Returns:
true iff we found a solution.

ParserException

saveResult

protected void saveResult()
                   throws ParserException
For PredicateList this does nothing. It is a place holder for something that a query must do when recursing. That is, if there is a combinations of constants that makes the query true, save the combination as an answer. But, for a PredicateList we nothing.

initializeVariableInformation

protected void initializeVariableInformation()
Setup the PredicateList with all information as to a variable and its locations in the predicate list. In this case it is all stored in a variable of type VariableInformation which stores all of the locations of a variable in the predicate list. In Query we will override this method so that all information is stored in a QueryVariableInformation which is a subclass of VariableInformation. QueryVariableInformatin includes the added information of what the current value is for each variable in the information list. This latter information is used for deriving and printing the solutions for a Query.

Precondition: none
Postcondition: variableInformation instanceof VariableInformation AND
  setUpVariableLocationMapping.Postcondition

See Also:
Source Code

keepOnGoing

protected boolean keepOnGoing(boolean validSolutionFound)
Should we continue finding all combinations of constants, if we are recursing over a predicate list, then we can stop the first time we find a true one, if this is a query, then we never stop. Since this is a PredicateList we stop when we find the first valid substitution. We will need to override this in Query.

Precondition: validSolutionFound is a value that will be used.
Postcondition: result = ¬ validSolutionFound

Parameters:
validSolutionFound - indicates whether or not we found a valid solution.
Returns:
true iff we did NOT find a valid solution.
